Beijing's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting more than 500 species of wildlife cities to "settle down" - Chinanews.com
2020-07-26 05:03:17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The capital's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting wildlife cities to "settle down"
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
(Reporter Wang Bin) Beijing Youth Daily reporter learned from the Municipal Bureau of Landscaping and Greening that in recent years, with the continuous improvement of the capital's natural ecological environment, the species and quantity of wild animals have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals inhabiting Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including brown pheasant, black stork and other national first-class protected animals, as well as impala, swan, grey crane, mandarin duck and other national second-class protected animals.
Whether planted in urban forests everywhere in the Second Ring Road or embedded in small and micro wetlands between buildings, it not only brings the wild interest of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In midsummer, Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of vitality.
A raccoon dog is playing leisurely by the mountain stream, while two badgers are fighting with each other.
Looking back, a wild boar couldn't help scratching against the bark. Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Management Office, said that by the end of 2019, in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares, there are 178 kinds of wild animals, including the national first-class protected animal golden eagle and the national second-class protected animal spoon chicken and impala, and nearly one-third of the wild animal species in the city can be seen here.
"In Songshan, wild animals are the real 'masters', and our staff can only be regarded as other people's' bodyguards' at best."
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the situation of wild animals and plants in the reserve on the spot, more than 30 professional patrol members patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes every day, and there will be a "big circle" every month, spending a whole day almost all over the reserve.
"During inspections, we should not only check and record biodiversity, but also check and install artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install field infrared cameras, and so on."
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in Songshan National Nature Reserve to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli introduced that with the continuous enrichment of biodiversity in the reserve in recent years, more and more wild animals appear in the camera, leopard cats, raccoons and pig badgers have become "resident guests", and the "appearance rate" of the national second-class protected animal Impala is also getting higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, director of the Wildlife and Wetland Protection Division of the Beijing Municipal Bureau of Landscaping and Greening, said that the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals in Beijing has increased from 461 in 1994 to more than 500 now, and the species and quantity of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
Wild animals are becoming more and more common in cities, which is closely related to the continuous upgrading of greening in the capital city in recent years.
In particular, the new round of afforestation and greening construction of one million mu starting in 2018 proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological function of forest land and green space, and highlight the concept of "near nature".
The planning strives to realize interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green space, so as to facilitate wild animals to "visit relatives and friends". The trees planted are also honey and food plants that animals like.
Black Land "Grows" Agricultural Modernizatio - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Harbin, July 26 th: Black land "grows" agricultural modernization
In midsummer, two pesticide spraying planes passed by the 10,000-mu high-yield demonstration field in the second operation station of the fifth management area of Friendship Farm, forming two white lines. The big characters "the first field in the world" planted with black rice seedlings in the green fields were particularly eye-catching.
Kong Lingqiang, the stationmaster of this operation station, said that this kind of plane can spray chemicals on more than 6,000 mu of cultivated land a day, and its efficiency is about 8 times that of unmanned aerial vehicles and hundreds of times that of manual work.
This farm is located in Youyi County, Heilongjiang Province, the largest grain-producing province in China. From the sound of rice cutting in the past to the sound of motors rumbling now, traditional Chinese farming and farms have transformed in this black soil belt.
In addition to airplanes, satellites are also used in the modern agricultural production of Friendship Farm.
Kong Lingqiang introduced that on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to achieve accurate fertilization, reduce agricultural investment and reduce pollution; on the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the standardized operation level of agricultural machinery in the field.
In this year's rice production process, the farm expanded the operating area of satellite navigation unmanned transplanting technology from 3,000 mu last year to 30,000 mu.
This technology makes seedling planting more uniform, maximizes the utilization of sunlight and cultivated land resources, and saves labor costs of 16 yuan per mu.
Farms try new technologies such as informatization and intelligence in agricultural production, forming the largest agricultural machinery group in China from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, at present, the total number of agricultural machinery on the farm is 49,000 units (pieces), and the comprehensive mechanization rate in the field reaches 99.8%.
Agricultural machinery operations achieve 100% GPS satellite navigation, 100% precision sowing in dry fields, and 100% high-horsepower locomotive operations in dry fields.
"Green agriculture, smart agriculture and digital agriculture are the exploration directions of agricultural modernization."
Liu Hualian, director of Friendship Farm, said.
The key to agricultural modernization lies in scientific and technological progress.
In recent years, Heilongjiang Land Reclamation, represented by farms, has played a demonstration and leading role in modern large-scale agriculture "aircraft carrier", and initially established a modern agricultural industrial system dominated by large-scale planting, standardized production and industrial management.
In the suburb of Youyi County, there is an agricultural machinery Expo Park covering an area of 350,000 square meters.
More than 140 sets (pieces) of agricultural machinery introduced and used by Heilongjiang Land Reclamation over the years are on display here.
These agricultural machinery and farms have witnessed the development of China's agricultural modernization.
Give up the small family for everyone-the mass transfer in Jiangkou River Lianwei, Hefei, Anhui Provinc - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26 th: Give up the small family for everyone-Anhui Hefei Jiangkou River Lianwei Mass Transfer Direct Strike
Xinhua News Agency reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu and Liu Xiacun
At 4 o'clock in the afternoon on July 25, Fu Kunbao, wearing rubber shoes covered with mud, went from the front room to the back room and was busy packing things back and forth with his wife Zhou Yan.
"I received a call from the village cadre to transfer, and I was still weeding in the field."
Fu Kunbao said that he has transferred more than 60 mu of land and planted rice, and now he is growing well. "I also took medicine yesterday, and the tools have not been cleaned up."
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer placed in the corner. "No one wants their home to be flooded, so let's give up the small home for everyone."
In order to cope with the continuous high water level pressure and possible heavy rainfall in Chaohu Lake, Hefei City, Anhui Province is preparing to open the flood diversion and storage of Jiangkou River Lianwei where Fu Kunbao's family is located on the 26th.
Jiangkou River Lianwei is located in Feixi County, close to Chaohu Levee.
There are thousands of villagers involved in Yandian Township and Sanhe Town who need to be transferred.
As of 16:00 on the 25th, the water level of Chaohu Lake, China's fifth largest freshwater lake, remained at a high level of 13.2 meters, exceeding the guaranteed water level by 0.7 meters.
Fu Kunbao's kitchen is clean, with a pot of pumpkin head vegetables on the table, eggs and some stewed vegetables in the refrigerator.
"I didn't expect to move. The water in Jiangkou River looks good at present."
Zhou Yan said that the home is a bungalow, and some large objects have not been decided where to put them yet.
"Pack up your valuables first. Large items such as refrigerators and televisions can be temporarily placed in high-lying neighbors or relatives."
Wang Liwen, a village cadre, gave Fu Kunbao advice.
Wang Liwen is responsible for the transfer and resettlement of 13 villagers, notifying and confirming each person's resettlement plan.
The nearest resettlement site from Fu Kunbao's home is Su Primary School in Yandian Township, about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to the big items, Fu Kunbao and his wife also had a headache of more than 1,000 catties of grain and some newly bought furniture.
"Food is ready to be dragged to relatives' homes, and furniture can't be moved."
As soon as the couple discussed, they put a stool under the newly bought bed and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6 pm, Fu Kunbao began to transport things to relatives' homes by tricycle, and Zhou Yan continued to clean up at home.
At 11 o'clock in the evening, the couple watched it back and forth at home, turned on the switch, and prepared to go to the resettlement site.
"I hope the water will return soon."
Fu Kunbao said.
At 9:30 a.m. on July 26, the reporter saw at the scene of Lianwei in Jiangkou River that the local area had made various preparations before flood diversion.
