The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic passenger planes registered in the United States, because the corrosion of the air check valves of the above-mentioned passenger planes may cause the engines to stop in the air.
The FAA said that so far, it has received four reports of engine parking of 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft in the air, so it has made emergency inspection requirements. The inspection targets are passenger aircraft parked continuously for 7 days or more and passenger aircraft that have flown less than 11 times so far after re-entering the flight.
The FAA warned that if the level 5 check valves of all two engines of the passenger plane are corroded, they may get stuck in the open position, causing the passenger plane to completely lose power and unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace this key component before the passenger plane is put into use again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the COVID-19 outbreak reduced travel demand, resulting in many passenger planes being sealed or used less, and "check valves are more likely to be corroded."
Boeing also said that it has advised airline operators to inspect the passenger planes involved in the instructions, and if problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in overhauling and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that passenger planes owned by major US airlines usually fly multiple times a day, but after the COVID-19 outbreak, a large number of passenger planes were grounded; with the slow growth of passenger travel demand recently, some passenger planes have been put into operation again.
The FAA did not release the details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its passenger planes was en route from Seattle, Washington to Austin, Texas on July 15 when an engine suddenly stalled and the passenger plane finally made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the engine of the passenger plane and had inspected the engines of six passenger planes in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that their passenger planes did not have engine flameout associated with air check valves.
Four American Airlines passenger planes will be inspected, and 28 United Airlines passenger planes will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 passenger planes, but did not say whether there had been engine flameout.
Many media reported that the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive is another impact on Boeing.
A Boeing 737MAX passenger plane of Indonesian Lion Airlines and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing 346 people in total.
This series of passenger planes were subsequently grounded worldwide, stopped production in January this year and resumed production in May.
FAA Director Steve Dixon admitted in June that the FAA had "made a mistake" in regulating Boeing with regard to the 737MAX passenger plane.
