Hoh Xil Tibetan antelope enters migration seaso - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of the Hoh Xil Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration that monitoring showed that Tibetan antelopes that had migrated to the Zhuonaihu area in the hinterland of Hoh Xil were gradually ending their litter and began to return to their original habitat with their cubs.
Monitoring images near Wudaoliang Protection Station show that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led three Tibetan antelope cubs through 3002 kilometers of Qinghai-Tibet Highway and Wudaoliang North Bridge on Qinghai-Tibet Railway, and Tibetan antelopes have begun to move back.
According to expert analysis, in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope cubs in the relocated sheep herd accounts for one quarter to one fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope herds.
Lian Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "In the early stage of migration, Tibetan antelopes face a higher risk of being preyed, so the number of cubs in the flock will be relatively small, and there may even be no cubs."
According to the statistics of Hoh Xil Management Office of Yangtze River Source Park of Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelopes has been increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelopes was 4,860, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Lian Xinming said: "It is expected that this year's migration of Tibetan antelopes will end in early September, and the number of Tibetan antelopes is expected to continue to increase."
Tibetan antelope is a national first-class protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet, Altun Mountain in Xinjiang and other places go to Zhuonaihu in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth to lambs.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert on Tibetan antelope protection in China and a researcher at Shaanxi Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said: "The migration of Tibetan antelopes is a process in which female Tibetan antelopes return to their habitats one after another after giving birth. At first, the returning population leaving the litter site is relatively large, but then Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats along different paths according to different geographical populations."
In order to ensure the safe relocation of the Tibetan antelope herd, the reporter learned that the Hoh Xil Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has arranged staff to continuously carry out video monitoring and patrol in the main relocation areas.
If Tibetan antelopes are found trying to cross the highway, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control as soon as possible to let the sheep pass through the wildlife passage safely and ensure that they are as little disturbed by human beings as possible on the way back.
So, how to relieve the summer heat in daily life?
Experts suggest that when going out in summer, try to avoid the high temperature period, and it is best not to walk or work in the hot sun around noon, because the sunshine is the strongest during this period, and the possibility of heatstroke is higher.
If you must go out at this time, you must do a good job of protection, such as playing a sunshade, wearing a sunshade hat, and wearing sunglasses. If conditions permit, it is best to apply sunscreen to prevent sunburn.
Clothes should be made of light-colored cotton, hemp and silk with good air permeability as far as possible, and chemical fiber clothing should be worn less, so as not to dissipate heat in time when sweating a lot and cause heatstroke.
In hot and sultry weather, prepare enough water to drink in time, and don't wait for thirst to drink water, because once you feel thirsty, your body is already short of water, and each time you drink 150 ml to 200 ml of water, drink warm boiled water, and don't drink ice water.
According to the temperature, the average person drinks 1.5 liters to 2 liters of water every day, while high-temperature workers drink 3 liters to 5 liters of water every day.
When sweating more, some salt water can be added appropriately to make up for the salt lost by sweating.
In addition, the human body is prone to potassium deficiency in summer, which makes people feel tired and tired. Potassium-containing tea is an excellent summer drink.
Eat more fruits and vegetables with high water content in summer, such as lettuce, cucumber, tomatoes, etc.; Fresh fruits, such as peaches, apricots, watermelons, melons and other water content is 80% to 90%, can be used to supplement water; Dairy products can not only replenish water, but also meet the nutritional needs of the body.
In addition, people working in high temperature environment should appropriately supplement drinks containing potassium, magnesium and other elements.
In summer, the days are long and the nights are short, the temperature is high, the metabolism of the human body is vigorous, the consumption is also large, and it is easy to feel tired.
Adequate sleep can relax all systems of the brain and body, which is not only conducive to work and study, but also a measure to prevent heatstroke.
Experts say the best time to go to bed is from 22:00 to 23:00, and the best time to get up is from 5:30 to 6:30.
Be careful not to lie under the air conditioning outlet and electric fan during sleep, so as not to suffer from air conditioning diseases and hot colds.
Experts suggest that people who are engaged in outdoor activities or high-temperature operations can carry heatstroke prevention drugs such as ten drops of water, Rendan, Huoxiang Zhengqi Water or Huoxiang Zhengqi Pills, or place them in the nearest workplace and use them at any time to prevent heatstroke.
