Brazilian study shows that hydroxychloroquine is ineffective in the treatment of mild and moderate COVID-19
Recently, a Brazilian study showed that hydroxychloroquine is ineffective in patients with mild and moderate COVID-19.
The research report was published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
Pakistani researchers divided 667 patients from 55 hospitals across the country into three groups and conducted clinical trials; This paper mainly compares the therapeutic effects of hydroxychloroquine alone or in combination with other antibiotics azithromycin, and analyzes whether it is helpful to improve the condition of mild and moderate COVID-19 patients.
The results show that hydroxychloroquine not only has no therapeutic effect, but may have damaging side effects on organs.
This research was jointly completed by many authoritative hospitals in Brazil, such as Hospital Israelita Albert Einstein, Heart Hospital (HCor), Hospital Sírio-Libanês, etc., Brazilian Clinical Research Institute (BCRI) and Brazilian Intensive Care Research Network (BRICNet).
