France increases military investment in spac - Xinhuanet
French Defense Minister Floran Paley said on the 24th that France will add hundreds of millions of euros to its space defense budget and develop space military forces to prevent "unfriendly actions" that other countries may make in outer space.
Paley told Provence on the same day that from 2019 to 2025, the expenditure budget of French space military projects will increase from 3.6 billion euros (about 4.2 billion US dollars) previously proposed to 4.3 billion euros (5 billion US dollars).
According to the French Military Planning Act from 2019 to 2025 approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to update its existing observation satellites and communication satellites in the future, launch three electromagnetic interception satellites, and improve the modernization level of space surveillance radar.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced in July last year that a space military command and an "aviation and space force" would be established within the French Air Force.
Paley said she will officially announce the establishment of the space force when she visits a military academy in Salon, Provence later.
Paley said that this space force belongs to the Air Force and will have 500 personnel by 2025.
She said: "In the past, people thought that space served the common interests of science, but this idea is gone forever. Now space is a place where countries compete for global hegemony."
Paley reiterated Macron's previous statement that France has no intention of provoking an arms race.
"We are by no means engaged in an arms race. But it is my responsibility to thoroughly recognize the threats we may face."
Paley recalled the surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy in 2017.
She said that "peeping" was a Russian satellite.
Russia denies this statement.
Paley said that France "soon" will have small patrol satellites that can detect and target "the black hands behind those unfriendly actions".
French media believe that the reason why France seeks to establish a space force is that US President Donald Trump asked the US Department of Defense to draft a bill to establish a space force in February last year.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act in December last year, approving the establishment of the Space Force, the sixth largest service in the United States.
Some experts worry that these US measures have accelerated the pace of militarization of US space and may trigger a new round of space arms race.
