Xinhua News Agency, Xiamen, July 26 (Yang Fushan, Zhang Shushan, Xu Jingyi) The Department of Vascular Surgery of Shanghai Changhai Hospital of Naval Military Medical University, a famous vascular surgery center in China, signed a contract with the Department of Vascular Surgery of Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University on the 25th to jointly set up a cooperation center to promote exchanges and cooperation between the two sides in the field of vascular surgery, especially in the field of aortic acute and severe diseases.
Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University said that after the vascular surgery of the two hospitals formally formed a cooperative unit, they will carry out remote consultation, formulate treatment plans with Changhai Hospital in real-time online consultation, select talents for further training, and jointly carry out surgical technical exchanges and teaching rounds every week; For complex cases, Changhai experts can be invited to the hospital for surgery according to the needs of patients, so that patients in southwest Fujian can enjoy the top medical resources in China without leaving the province.
The two hospitals will also work together to carry out innovative scientific research on surgery, popular science and early screening of aortic diseases, and so on.
A special seminar on aorta sponsored by Beijing Health Promotion Association and hosted by Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University was held in Xiamen on the same day.
The above-mentioned two well-known hospitals in Shanghai and Xiamen held a signing ceremony for the Vascular Surgery Cooperation Center at the same time at the meeting, announcing the formation of a cooperative unit to jointly improve the treatment level of vascular surgery-related diseases in southwest Fujian.
The Department of Vascular Surgery of Shanghai Changhai Hospital is the only vascular surgery research institute in the army and the only clinical medical center for vascular system diseases in Shanghai. It is also the first national key discipline of vascular surgery. It has led the establishment of the Endovascular Angiology Professional Committee of the Chinese Medical Doctor Association and is a top team with profound accumulation in the industry.
Professor Huang Xiaojin, Director of Vascular Surgery, Zhongshan Hospital Affiliated to Xiamen University, was interviewed by the media.
The Department of Vascular Surgery of Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University is the first independent discipline of vascular surgery in Fujian Province. It has long been committed to the diagnosis and treatment of aortic and peripheral vascular diseases, and was approved to build a provincial key clinical specialty in 2018.
In the treatment of aortic diseases, in addition to the treatment of dissecting aneurysms and aortic aneurysms, he has rich experience in emergency ruptured aortic aneurysms.
"The Department of Vascular Surgery of Zhongshan Hospital Affiliated to Xiamen University is outstanding in this region from the history of development, the breadth, difficulty and complexity of the operation. Therefore, this time we set up a cooperation center. In addition to the aorta, we can also carry out all-round in-depth cooperation in medicine, teaching and scientific research in the diagnosis and treatment of lower limb arteries, carotid arteries and other diseases."
Professor Feng Rui, deputy director of vascular surgery at Shanghai Changhai Hospital, said.
Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University and Shanghai Changhai Hospital signed a contract in 2018 to establish "Li Zhaoshen Famous Doctor Studio" in the Department of Gastroenterology.
Professor Huang Xiaojin, director of the hospital's vascular surgery department, said in an interview with Chinanews.com that the hospital's vascular surgery department has also had a long history of exchanges with Changhai Hospital. This time, the two hospitals formally formed a cooperative unit, bringing cooperation and exchanges between the two sides to a new level.
He said that the hospital will regularly invite Shanghai experts to Xiamen to carry out surgical technical exchanges, teaching rounds, and discussion of difficult cases. At the same time, it will further carry out remote consultation, which is currently planned to be held once a week. In addition, the department will also send personnel for further study and exchange to strengthen the training and development of discipline talents.
The reporter learned at the meeting that vascular disease is the largest cause of death in China, and the aorta, as the main road of various organs of the human body, flows from the heart to the whole body and plays an important role.
The occurrence of aortic disease is often accompanied by high risk, high mortality and high difficulty in treatment. The thickest section of the aorta has a diameter of 4cm. Once a hemangioma is formed, rupture occurs, or vascular intima rupture produces dissection, it will cause massive hemorrhage, which is very dangerous.
In recent years, with the change of people's lifestyle and the acceleration of the pace of life, China has become the world's largest country in hypertension, and aortic diseases have also increased. Nowadays, with the development of surgical technology and industrial materials, the treatment of aortic diseases continues to develop in the direction of minimally invasive, rapid and efficient.
Doctors can properly "change lanes" for blood flow by puncturing the thigh and placing stents in the aorta, so as to avoid the impact on aneurysms or ruptured dissections and achieve good therapeutic effects. Some operations even require local anesthesia.
This academic seminar invited more than ten domestic experts to discuss the new progress in the treatment of aortic diseases, and carried out cutting-edge technical training and difficult case discussion in the form of conference salons.
The reporter learned at the meeting that with the development of surgical technology and industrial materials, the treatment of aortic diseases is currently developing in a minimally invasive, rapid and efficient direction.
