The overall stability of employment and prices shows that the economy has "temperature"
Lin Huocan, a reporter from Economic Daily China Economic Network
In the first half of this year, in the face of the impact of the COVID-19 epidemic, China made overall plans to promote epidemic prevention and control and economic and social development. The epidemic prevention and control situation continued to improve, the steady economic recovery was obvious, and the employment and price performance closely related to people's livelihood were generally stable. China's economy handed over a report card of economic operation with temperature.
In the first two months of this year, the surveyed unemployment rate rose.
Especially in February, the production and operation activities of many enterprises were basically in a state of shutdown, the employment demand of enterprises decreased, recruitment was delayed or cancelled, and the unemployment rate surveyed in cities and towns increased.
With the gradual improvement of the epidemic prevention and control situation, the production and living order of the whole society has been continuously restored.
The CPC Central Committee adheres to the general tone of seeking progress while maintaining stability, further intensifies macro policy hedging, comprehensively strengthens the employment priority policy, and actively promotes the work of assisting enterprises to stabilize posts and expand employment.
China has stepped up policies to hedge and stabilize jobs, played a combination of policies of "reduction and exemption, slow return and compensation", phased reduction and exemption of three social insurance unit contributions, allowed deferred payment of social insurance premiums, expanded the benefits of stable post return of unemployment insurance for small and medium-sized enterprises and the policy of replacing training with work, and provided absorption subsidies and probation subsidies for enterprises to absorb the employment of key groups.
With the implementation of various employment stabilization policies, the employment demand of enterprises has steadily picked up, the employment situation has gradually improved, and the surveyed unemployment rate in cities and towns has gradually declined. In June, the surveyed unemployment rate was 5.7%.
Zhang Yi, director of the Department of Population and Employment Statistics of the National Bureau of Statistics, said that in the second quarter, various employment policies continued to take effect, and the labor force who withdrew due to the impact of the epidemic in the early stage returned one after another. The urban labor participation rate in June increased by about 10 percentage points compared with February, which was close
Data show that the total urban employment in June increased by more than 19% compared with February, and most industries reached the pre-epidemic level; The average weekly working hours of employees in enterprises reached 46.8 hours, 6.6 hours higher than that in February and 0.1 hours higher than that in January.
Prices are also related to thousands of households.
In January this year, CPI rose 5.4% year-on-year, setting a new high for many years.
Entering February, although the year-on-year increase of CPI fell slightly, it was still in the "5 range".
The year-on-year increase of CPI is at a high level, which is not only driven by consumer demand before the Spring Festival, but also by the wrong month of the Spring Festival and a low year-on-year base.
However, the impact of the COVID-19 epidemic on prices is particularly obvious.
Affected by epidemic prevention and control, logistics delays, untimely supply of materials and increased transportation costs occurred all over the country in January and February. In addition, some citizens hoarded and snapped up, and the prices of some daily necessities increased significantly.
In order to cope with the disturbance of epidemic prevention and control to the price situation, relevant departments have brought important living materials into the scope of emergency transportation guarantee to ensure smooth transportation of materials.
Under the action of a series of policy measures, the market supply of vegetables, melons and fruits has been strongly guaranteed.
In response to the rapid rise in pork prices at the beginning of this year, after the central government issued the policy of ensuring supply and stabilizing prices, various regions and departments quickly implemented it, and the supply of pork reserves improved significantly, pig production capacity recovered in an orderly manner, and the production and marketing order gradually became normal.
Since March, pork prices have continued to decline, driving the year-on-year increase in food prices back to 10.6% in May; In June, pork prices rose slightly month-on-month due to factors such as the slowdown in pig slaughter, reduced imports and the rebound in group consumer demand.
Seasonal changes in fresh vegetable prices are obvious, with an average increase of 3.4% in the first half of the year.
Affected by the high base of comparison in the same period last year, fresh fruit prices continued to decline year on year, with an average decline of 13.3% in the first half of the year
The basic livelihood of the masses has been effectively guaranteed, and the overall economic and social situation has remained stable and orderly.
With the gradual recovery of transportation and logistics, all localities have increased their efforts to ensure supply, and the market supply and demand situation has improved.
Starting in March, CPI fell month on month for four consecutive months, and the year-on-year increase also dropped from 4.3% in March to 2.5% in June, and the overall price level returned to stability.
In the second half of the year, China's prices will continue to maintain a moderate level, and the overall inflationary pressure is not great, but it is still necessary to promote the restoration of production and living order on the premise of normalizing epidemic prevention and control.
Effectively respond to natural disasters such as floods and droughts in major agricultural production areas such as grain, fruits and vegetables, strengthen market supervision, and resolutely crack down on hoarding, price hikes and other behaviors that disrupt market order.
