This series of measures quickly achieved positive results. By mid-May, the number of newly confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Israel in a single day had dropped to single digits.
With the epidemic under control, Israel's various prevention and control measures have been fully unsealed. Since June, the number of newly diagnosed COVID-19 has gradually rebounded.
Especially after entering July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, there are more than 1,500 new cases in Israel every day for 8 days, and as of July 25, there were 916 new cases on that day.
As of July 25, there were 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
Facing the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed public entertainment places such as gymnasiums, swimming pools, bars and nightclubs, and introduced a policy of restricting public transportation, stipulating that the maximum number of passengers per bus should not exceed 20.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictive measures, including the implementation of "city closure" on weekends, which stipulated that "city closure" would be implemented from 17:00 every Friday to 5:00 every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but shops, shopping centers, barbershops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while supermarkets, pharmacies and other basic service places will remain open.
