At Banong Zhuokang sentry post, platoon leader Yu Wang and a soldier stood guard on duty.
In this place where the annual average temperature is more than ten degrees below zero, a row of simple barracks stands at the mountain pass, and a national flag flutters in the wind not far from the barracks. Soldiers stand guard in the wind every day and need to patrol at higher altitude regularly.
Soldiers need to use both hands and feet to climb the steep slope of rocky piles.
It was late July, when flowers and plants flourished at low altitude, while in Banong Zhuokang, only the ravine behind the barracks had relatively dense green.
Gao Peng, a soldier who has been stationed at the outpost for six years, pointed to the ravine and said that this is their back garden. Only in July and August can grass grow slowly every year. Soon after, it all turns yellow and is covered with snow.
It may take about 9 hours to patrol on foot.
Under the harsh plateau environment, the soldiers stationed here are accompanied by snow-capped mountains and glaciers all the year round, and they also regularly patrol mountain passes at higher altitudes.
A few days ago, a patrol composed of eight soldiers, led by instructor Liang Yixin, once again embarked on the patrol road.
Each soldier carried a weight of about 30 kg and headed for the target point early in the morning.
On the way, a soldier turned against Gao and his comrades gave emergency rescue.
In addition to patrol missions, the soldiers at the Banong Zhuokang sentry post have to carry out tactical and physical training every day.
As time goes by, the altitude is rising, the oxygen content is getting lower and lower, and the physical strength is constantly overdrawn. These factors test the will of the patrol members.
They gritted their teeth and insisted, crossing several landslides and dangerous beaches one after another.
At about 16 o'clock, it was lunch time for the patrol members. They took out their own dry food and sat on the spot at an altitude of more than 5,700 meters, accompanied by sleet and supplemented their physical strength with food.
Soldiers at Banong Zhuokang sentry post carry out tactical and physical training.
During the break, they will play cards together, and the losers will do push-ups, which can not only entertain but also exercise their physical fitness.
After a short rest in the cold wind, they climbed to the target point of the patrol, took out the national flag on the mountain pass and solemnly swore.
Behind them are snow-capped mountains, and in front of them are dozens of kilometers of no man's land. They are the safest guardians of the country.
