Understand what is the professional grade difference before volunteering to fill in the report.
Every year, when filling in college entrance examination volunteers, some students or parents do not understand the terms involved in volunteering, which affects volunteering.
This year, Beijing Jiaotong University, Beijing University of Science and Technology, Beijing University of Posts and Telecommunications, Beijing Forestry University and Beijing University of Chemical Technology jointly issued the 2020 enrollment policy to cancel the professional grade difference.
What does professional grade difference mean and what is the significance in voluntary reporting?
There are three ways to allocate professional rules
Experts remind that before filling in the volunteer form, you must carefully read the "Admissions Regulations" of your favorite school to understand the admission rules of colleges and universities, including the transfer ratio, professional distribution rules, etc.
Professional distribution rules refer to the three main ways of professional admission: professional priority, score priority and professional grade difference after the transfer of files in colleges and universities.
The specific method used by colleges and universities will be specified in the enrollment regulations.
However, there are also some colleges and universities whose admission principle is to give priority to the total score, and there is no grade difference between majors.
That is to say, candidates within the admission range will be queued up according to the total score. When the score does not reach the first professional voluntary admission score line, it will be seen whether it has reached the second professional voluntary admission score line, and so on until the last professional voluntary is admitted, and there is no grade difference between the professional voluntary.
The so-called "professional grade difference" means that when colleges and universities arrange candidates' majors, they determine the admission majors of volunteer candidates of different majors according to one or several score values published in the enrollment regulations. This score value is "professional grade difference".
That is, the score difference between the first professional volunteer and the non-first professional volunteer of the college when admitting candidates, and the grade difference scores between the professional volunteers, such as 3 points, 2 points, 1 point, etc.
For example.
Suppose student Xiaoming applied for college A and scored 560 points. His professional volunteers are: computer, international trade, automation, mechanical engineering and e-commerce. The professional admission of college A adopts the method of professional grade difference, and the grade difference is divided into 2 points, 1 point, 1 point and 0 point.
In the professional allocation, if Xiaoming's first professional volunteer meets the professional admission requirements and the major has a planned balance, then Xiaoming is admitted to the "computer" major; If the computer is not admitted, his score will be subtracted by 2 points, and candidates who volunteer to apply for "international trade" with the first major will be ranked according to the score of 558 points to determine whether they meet the professional admission conditions; If it is still not satisfied, the score will be subtracted by 1 point (that is, 557 points) for the "automatic" admission of the third professional volunteer; If it is still not satisfied, the score will be subtracted by 1 point (that is, 556 points) for admission to the fourth major, If the follow-up major still cannot meet its professional wishes, the score will not be reduced, and so on.
Different universities have different professional grade differences
With the popularization of parallel volunteering, many colleges and universities have now cancelled the professional grade difference, but some colleges and universities still retain this method this year. Judging from the "enrollment regulations" announced by various colleges and universities, more than 20 universities have set up professional grade differences this year.
For example, Sichuan Agricultural University, Shandong University of Science and Technology, Heilongjiang University of Traditional Chinese Medicine, Jiangsu University of Science and Technology, Jiangxi Normal University, Chengdu Medical College, Northeast Dianli University, Jimei University, Nanjing Medical University, Nanjing University of Technology, Ningxia University, Shandong University of Technology, China Civil Aviation Flight College, etc.
In these universities, each university has different professional grades.
Some colleges and universities have a grade difference in each major, such as Ningxia University. Candidates whose files have been submitted to the school are admitted according to the order in which candidates fill in their professional volunteers by 1 point in turn.
However, some universities have set different professional grades between different majors.
For example, Jimei University, the total score of professional volunteer grade difference is 4 points, that is, the grade difference between the first professional volunteer and other professional volunteers is 3 points, and there is no grade difference between other professional volunteers, which is regarded as parallel volunteer, and the professional grade difference between other professional volunteers and transfer professional volunteers is 1 point.
When filling in their volunteers, candidates and parents must carefully read the admission policy of the reported school to see if there is a professional grade difference and what is the form of the grade difference. While fully considering the scores, they should also reasonably analyze the schools and majors to be selected. If the colleges and universities clearly adopt the grade difference method for admission in the enrollment regulations, candidates should pay attention to the gradient between the majors when choosing majors to improve the admission probability.
